j26:OpenTelemetryInstrumentation a pl:Pattern ;
    rdfs:label "OPENTELEMETRY INSTRUMENTATION" ;
    pl:hasNumber 29 ;
    pl:hasConfidence 1 ;
    pl:hasCategory j26:InfrastructureCategory ;
    pl:hasSlug "opentelemetry-instrumentation" ;
    pl:hasEvocativeImage "Observability is not added later; it is generated with the code." ;
    pl:hasContext """Service-level observability requires span creation, metric recording, and log correlation. Adding these manually to every service method is tedious and inconsistent. Teams add spans to some methods and not others. Span names are inconsistent. Attributes are missing. The result is a tracing backend full of gaps and inconsistencies that make debugging harder, not easier.

When observability code is generated alongside business code, it is consistent by construction. Every service method has a span. Every span has the same set of attributes. The trace is complete because the generator applied the same template to every method.""" ;
    pl:hasProblem "Observability code added manually is inconsistent, incomplete, and often wrong." ;
    pl:hasSolution """Generate OpenTelemetry instrumentation for every @Service method as part of the code generation. The ontology marks which operations are observable via java26:observable true. ggen generates @WithSpan annotations for simple cases and manual Span creation with error recording for complex cases. Every span records the operation name, aggregate class, and correlation ID from the ScopedValue request context (Pattern 33).

Metrics are also generated: counters for operation invocations, histograms for operation duration. These are named consistently: {aggregate}.{operation}.count and {aggregate}.{operation}.duration.""" ;
    pl:hasImplementation """ggen detects java26:observable true on java26:AggregateRoot and generates instrumented service wrapper classes. Simple methods receive @WithSpan. Methods that need custom attributes or error recording receive manual Tracer injection and Span lifecycle management in a try-finally block.""" ;
    j26:hasScaleLevel "leaf" ;
    j26:javaVersion "26" ;;;
    j26:hasGgenSyncInvocation "ggen sync --rule opentelemetry-instrumentation" ;.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

j26:JakartaValidationConstraints a pl:Pattern ;
    rdfs:label "JAKARTA VALIDATION CONSTRAINTS" ;
    pl:hasNumber 30 ;
    pl:hasConfidence 1 ;
    pl:hasCategory j26:InfrastructureCategory ;
    pl:hasSlug "jakarta-validation-constraints" ;
    pl:hasEvocativeImage "The constraint lives in the type, not in the if-statement." ;
    pl:hasContext """Input validation scattered across controllers and services is inconsistent. Some fields are validated in the controller, others in the service, others not at all. The validation rules for a field (maximum length, allowed pattern) are scattered across multiple files and often duplicated with slight differences. Gaps where invalid data enters the system are common.

SHACL shapes in the ontology are the natural place to declare field constraints: sh:maxLength, sh:pattern, sh:minInclusive, sh:in for enum values. These are formal assertions about the shape of valid data. ggen maps SHACL shapes to Jakarta Validation annotations, generating a single source of truth for all validation rules.""" ;
    pl:hasProblem "Validation logic duplicated across layers creates gaps where invalid data can enter the system." ;
    pl:hasSolution """Express validation constraints in the ontology via SHACL shapes. ggen generates @NotNull, @NotBlank, @Size, @Pattern, @Min, @Max, and custom @Constraint annotations from SHACL property shapes. The SHACL shape file (.specify/shapes/domain.shacl.ttl) is separate from the domain ontology but references the same classes. @Valid on controller parameters and service command records triggers the validation automatically.

sh:maxLength → @Size(max=N), sh:minLength → @Size(min=N), sh:pattern → @Pattern(regexp="..."), sh:minInclusive → @Min(N), sh:maxInclusive → @Max(N), sh:in → custom @AllowedValues constraint.""" ;
    pl:hasImplementation """ggen reads SHACL NodeShape files and maps each sh:PropertyShape constraint to the corresponding Jakarta Validation annotation. The annotations are generated onto the command records (co-located with the service) rather than onto the entity, keeping the validation at the input boundary rather than deep in the domain.""" ;
    j26:hasScaleLevel "leaf" ;
    j26:javaVersion "26" ;;;
    j26:hasGgenSyncInvocation "ggen sync --rule jakarta-validation-constraints" ;.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

j26:SpringCacheAbstraction a pl:Pattern ;
    rdfs:label "SPRING CACHE ABSTRACTION" ;
    pl:hasNumber 31 ;
    pl:hasConfidence 1 ;
    pl:hasCategory j26:InfrastructureCategory ;
    pl:hasSlug "spring-cache-abstraction" ;
    pl:hasEvocativeImage "Read many times, compute once — the cache is the memory of the service." ;
    pl:hasContext """Read-heavy services benefit from caching but cache configuration is scattered across the codebase. @Cacheable annotations are added inconsistently. Some findById methods are cached but not findAll. Cache eviction is forgotten after save and delete, leaving stale entries. The cache key strategy is inconsistent across services, making cache warming and invalidation scripts brittle.

When caching rules are derived from the ontology, they are applied consistently. The same generator that adds @Cacheable to findById also adds @CacheEvict to save and delete. The cache name is derived from the entity class name, making it predictable.""" ;
    pl:hasProblem "Manually added @Cacheable annotations diverge from the actual access patterns." ;
    pl:hasSolution """Mark read-heavy entities as java26:cacheable in the ontology. ggen generates @Cacheable, @CacheEvict, and @CachePut on the appropriate service methods. @Cacheable(\"products\") on findById uses the entity ID as the cache key. @CacheEvict(\"products\", allEntries=false) on save evicts the specific entry. @CacheEvict(\"products\", allEntries=true) on deleteAll evicts everything. The cache name is derived from the entity rdfs:label.""" ;
    pl:hasImplementation """ggen detects java26:cacheable true on java26:AggregateRoot and generates the @EnableCaching configuration, the @Cacheable/@CacheEvict/@CachePut annotations on service methods, and a CacheConfig inner class that defines the cache TTL from java26:cacheTtlSeconds.""" ;
    j26:hasScaleLevel "leaf" ;
    j26:javaVersion "26" ;;;
    j26:hasGgenSyncInvocation "ggen sync --rule spring-cache-abstraction" ;.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

j26:JsonSerializer a pl:Pattern ;
    rdfs:label "JSON SERIALIZER" ;
    pl:hasNumber 32 ;
    pl:hasConfidence 1 ;
    pl:hasCategory j26:InfrastructureCategory ;
    pl:hasSlug "json-serializer" ;
    pl:hasEvocativeImage "The wire format is not the domain; the serializer is the translator." ;
    pl:hasContext """Jackson JSON serialization requires @JsonProperty, @JsonIgnore, custom serializers for types like Instant, UUID, and BigDecimal. These annotations pollute domain types. An @Entity class with @JsonProperty, @JsonIgnore, and @JsonSerialize annotations is serving two masters: the ORM and the HTTP layer. When the wire format changes, the entity class changes. When the entity changes, the serialization behavior changes.

Separating domain types from their wire representation using DTO records keeps both concerns clean. The DTO record is the wire format. The entity is the domain. The factory method (from) is the explicit translation between them.""" ;
    pl:hasProblem "Serialization annotations pollute domain types and create tight coupling to the wire format." ;
    pl:hasSolution """Generate dedicated DTO records that handle all serialization concerns, keeping the domain types clean. Each java26:ValueObject or java26:AggregateRoot with java26:exposeAsRest true gets a generated DTO record with: @JsonProperty for field name customization, @JsonIgnore for internal fields, custom serializers for Instant (ISO-8601) and BigDecimal (string for precision), and a static from(Entity) factory method.

The DTO record is a snapshot of the entity at a point in time — immutable, serializable, and safe to pass across the HTTP boundary.""" ;
    pl:hasImplementation """ggen generates a DTO record for every java26:AggregateRoot with java26:exposeAsRest true. Field type mappings: UUID → String (for JSON compatibility), Instant → String with ISO-8601 format, BigDecimal → String (to preserve precision in JSON), enums → their getValue() string. The from(Entity) factory is generated with the correct field mapping.""" ;
    j26:hasScaleLevel "leaf" ;
    j26:javaVersion "26" ;;;
    j26:hasGgenSyncInvocation "ggen sync --rule json-serializer" ;.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

j26:ScopedValueRequestContext a pl:Pattern ;
    rdfs:label "SCOPED VALUE REQUEST CONTEXT" ;
    pl:hasNumber 33 ;
    pl:hasConfidence 1 ;
    pl:hasCategory j26:InfrastructureCategory ;
    pl:hasSlug "scoped-value-request-context" ;
    pl:hasEvocativeImage "The request carries its context invisibly, accessible anywhere in the call stack without passing parameters." ;
    pl:hasContext """Request context (user ID, correlation ID, tenant ID) needs to be accessible throughout the call stack without threading it through every method parameter. The traditional solution is ThreadLocal, but ThreadLocal fails with virtual threads: a virtual thread can be mounted on different platform threads during its lifetime, and ThreadLocal is scoped to the platform thread. Child threads don't inherit parent ThreadLocals.

ScopedValue (JEP 446, finalized in Java 26) was designed specifically for virtual threads. A ScopedValue is bound at the entry point of a request and is accessible in the same virtual thread's call stack — including all frames called transitively. Child threads created by StructuredTaskScope inherit the parent's ScopedValues. No parameter passing required.""" ;
    pl:hasProblem "ThreadLocal variables fail with virtual threads; passing context explicitly is verbose." ;
    pl:hasSolution """Use ScopedValue (JEP 446) to bind request context at the boundary and access it anywhere in the virtual thread's call stack. Generate the ScopedValue declarations from the ontology. In the ontology, declare java26:RequestContext with the list of context fields (userId, correlationId, tenantId). ggen generates a RequestContext record and a ScopedValues holder class. The Spring filter binds the context via ScopedValue.where().run() at the request entry point.

ScopedValues are immutable within a scope: you cannot set a ScopedValue after binding. This eliminates a class of ThreadLocal bugs where code modifies the shared thread-local state unexpectedly.""" ;
    pl:hasImplementation """ggen reads java26:RequestContext class definitions and generates a RequestContext record with the declared fields, a ScopedValues holder with one ScopedValue<RequestContext> constant, and a Spring OncePerRequestFilter that binds the context from HTTP headers and passes control to the filter chain inside ScopedValue.where().run().""" ;
    j26:hasScaleLevel "leaf" ;
    j26:javaVersion "26" ;;;
    j26:hasGgenSyncInvocation "ggen sync --rule scoped-value-request-context" ;.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

j26:MavenModulePom a pl:Pattern ;
    rdfs:label "MAVEN MODULE POM" ;
    pl:hasNumber 34 ;
    pl:hasConfidence 1 ;
    pl:hasCategory j26:InfrastructureCategory ;
    pl:hasSlug "maven-module-pom" ;
    pl:hasEvocativeImage "The build file is just another projection of the domain's dependency graph." ;
    pl:hasContext """Multi-module Maven projects require consistent pom.xml files with correct parent references, dependency management, and plugin configuration. Manually maintained pom.xml files diverge from each other: one module uses Java 21, another Java 26. One module uses Spring Boot 3.2, another 3.4. The Surefire plugin version is inconsistent. These divergences cause build failures that are hard to trace and time-consuming to fix.

The dependency relationships between modules are a graph: module B depends on module A. This graph is part of the domain's information architecture and belongs in the ontology. Once the module graph is in the ontology, generating consistent pom.xml files is straightforward: ggen reads the module declarations and generates a parent pom and all module poms from the same template.""" ;
    pl:hasProblem "Manually maintained pom.xml files diverge from each other and from the dependency graph." ;
    pl:hasSolution """Generate pom.xml files from the ontology's module declarations. The parent pom and all module poms are consistent because they come from the same source. In the ontology, declare java26:MavenModule instances with their groupId, artifactId, Java version, and dependencies. ggen generates the parent pom with <dependencyManagement> and all module poms with the correct <parent> reference and <dependencies>. ggen sync regenerates pom.xml whenever the ontology changes.

A BOM (Bill of Materials) pom is also generated from java26:BomModule — centralizing dependency version management across all modules.""" ;
    pl:hasImplementation """ggen reads java26:MavenModule declarations and generates one pom.xml per module in the correct directory. The parent pom aggregates all modules in <modules>. Dependency versions are centralized in the parent <dependencyManagement>. Plugin versions are standardized across all modules from a shared plugin configuration in the parent.""" ;
    j26:hasScaleLevel "leaf" ;
    j26:javaVersion "26" ;;;
    j26:hasGgenSyncInvocation "ggen sync --rule maven-module-pom" ;.

